result.execSummary:
The defendant Tatijahna Nate Burse was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Tatijahna Nate Burse is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Tatijahna Nate Burse was found guilty of Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Tatijahna Nate Burse was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
9:27 AM PLEA/SENTENCING AND ARRAIGNMENT. Defendant Tatijahna Nate Burse in court.  Plaintiff State of Wisconsin in court.  Attorney Mark Adam Fruehauf in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. State indicates defendant will plea to counts 1 and 4, recommends 90 days each count, concurrent, imposed and stayed 18 months, concurrent probation, conditions of probation to be. 10 days jail, 10 credit, $50 plus costs, DOC programming, remaining counts will be dismissed.  Attorney Craker acknowledges information, waives reading with respect to the arraignment.  
Court recounts charges and possible penalties. Defendant pleads guilty to both counts. Court informs defendant of rights given up by their plea. Attorney stipulates to a factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been knowingly and voluntarily made. Court finds Defendant understands all the rights they are waiving by their plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered. Remaining charges dismissed.
State notes no criminal convictions in the past. 
Court orders 90 days each, concurrent imposed and stayed for 18 months, 10 days jail, 10 days credit, $50 plus costs, DOC programming. Bail applied, remaining to be returned to posting party.
